		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>Traditional methods of studying neural coding characterize the encoding of known stimuli in average neural responses. Organisms face nearly the opposite task-decoding short segments of a spike train to extract information about an unknown, time-varying stimulus. Here we present strategies for characterizing the neural code from the point of view of the organism, culminating in algorithms for real-time stimulus reconstruction based on a single sample of the spike train. These methods are applied to the design and analysis of experiments on an identified movement-sensitive neuron in the fly visual system. As far as we know this is the first instance in which a direct &quot;reading&quot; of the neural code has been accomplished.</p>
			</abstract>
